is was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Gwenllian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>gwen</i>, the feminine form of <i>gwyn</i> ‘white, fair; blessed, holy’ (  see  Gwen  ) + <i>lliant</i> ‘flood, flow’ (probably in the transferred sense ‘foamy’ or ‘white’, referring to a pale complexion)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwenllian ferch Llywelyn was born in 1420, in Llangeler, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Llywelyn y Cryth ap Rhys, was 54 and her mother, Mrs. Llywelyn y Cryth ap Rhys, was 50. She had at least 2 sons with John ap Jenkin."},"et":{"1420–":"1420–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1396–1457":"1396–1457","1397–Female":"1397–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1402–Female":"1402–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1409–Male":"1409–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1474–1549":"1474–1549","–Male":"Surnud","1367–1464":"1367–1464","1371–Female":"1371–Surnud","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1371":"1371","1402":"1402","1457":"1457","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","Abt 1474":"umbes 1474","1464":"1464","1474":"1474","1397":"1397","1409":"1409","1549":"1549","Wales":"Wales","Meisgyn, Pen y lan, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Pen-y-lan, Glamorg